We build a computer vision model for malaria detection. In this notebook we work on Milestone 2, which consists in building the model and experimenting on its characteristics (architecture, hyperparameters, etc) for improved performances.

The files have been extracted to the local session of Google Colab. The extracted folder would have the following structure:

The extracted folder has different folders for train and test data which further contains the different sizes of images for parasitized and uninfected cells within the respective folder name.

The size of all images must be the same and should be converted to 4D arrays so that they can be used as an input for the convolutional neural network. Also, we need to create the labels for both types of images to be able to train and test the model.

Let's do the same for the training data first and then we will use the same code for the test data as well.

In [ ]:
#Storing the path of the extracted "train" folder 
train_dir = '/content/cell_images/train'

#Size of image so that each image has the same size
SIZE = 64

#Empty list to store the training images after they are converted to NumPy arrays
train_images = []

#Empty list to store the training labels (0 - uninfected, 1 - parasitized)
train_labels = []
In [ ]:
#We will run the same code for "parasitized" as well as "uninfected" folders within the "train" folder
for folder_name in ['/parasitized/', '/uninfected/']:
    
    #Path of the folder
    images_path = os.listdir(train_dir + folder_name)

    for i, image_name in enumerate(images_path):
        try:
            #Opening each image using the path of that image
            image = Image.open(train_dir + folder_name + image_name)

            #Resizing each image to (224,224)
            image = image.resize((SIZE, SIZE))

            #Converting images to arrays and appending that array to the empty list defined above
            train_images.append(np.array(image))

            #Creating labels for parasitized and uninfected images
            if folder_name=='/parasitized/':
                train_labels.append(1)
            else:
                train_labels.append(0)
        except Exception:
            pass       

#Converting lists to arrays
train_images = np.array(train_images)
train_labels = np.array(train_labels)

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# I modified this into a function for brievety
def prediction_report(model,test_dataset):
  pred = model.predict(test_dataset)
  pred = np.argmax(pred,axis = -1) 
  y_true = np.argmax(test_labels,axis = -1)

  #Printing the classification report
  print(classification_report(y_true,pred))

  #Plotting the heatmap using confusion matrix
  cm = confusion_matrix(y_true,pred)
  plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
  sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.0f', xticklabels=['Uninfected', 'Parasitized'], yticklabels=['Uninfected', 'Parasitized'])
  plt.ylabel('Actual')
  plt.xlabel('Predicted')
  plt.show()

# function to plot train and validation accuracy 
def plot_accuracy(history):
    N = len(history.history["accuracy"])
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history.history["accuracy"], label="train_accuracy", ls='--')
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history.history["val_accuracy"], label="val_accuracy", ls='--')
    plt.title("Accuracy vs Epoch")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")

Base Model (CNN0)¶

Note: The Base Model has been fully built and evaluated with all outputs shown to give an idea about the process of the creation and evaluation of the performance of a CNN architecture. A similar process can be followed in iterating to build better-performing CNN architectures.

For consistency, hereafter we refer to the base model as CNN0.

Building the model ¶

In [ ]:
#creating sequential model
model=Sequential()
model.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu",input_shape=(64,64,3)))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Conv2D(filters=32,kernel_size=2,padding="same",activation="relu"))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(512,activation="relu"))
model.add(Dropout(0.4))
model.add(Dense(2,activation="softmax"))#2 represent output layer neurons 
model.summary()

Notes on CNN0:¶

The base model CNN0 consists of 3 convolution+maxpool layers followed by a single dense (fully-connected) layer. This is already a very good model for the following reasons:

  • It has 95% accuracy on the test data (woth accuracy chosen here as the scoring metric).
  • It also has great precision, recall and other metrics for binary classification (aroun 95%).
  • It doesnt seem overfitted, as seen by accuracy converging with epochs to similar values on the training and validation datasets.

Analysis of CNN0 Model Errors¶

In this section we look at model errors from CNN0. Misclassification is rare (5%) so we focus on these cases to understand the reasons and seek potential improvements.

In [ ]:
# Load model CNN0
from tensorflow.keras.models import load_model
model = load_model('/content/drive/MyDrive/Data/CNN0.h5')

y_pred_proba = model.predict(test_images)# predicted probability (two classes)
y_pred = np.argmax(y_pred_proba,axis = -1)# convert boolean
y_true = np.argmax(test_labels,axis = -1)

# Build database of misclassified images
misclass_images=[]
misclass_labels=[]
misclass_probas=[]# predicted probability 0-1
misclass_index=[]# save index from full database
for count,(i,j,k,l) in enumerate(zip(test_images,y_pred,y_true,y_pred_proba)):
  if j != k:
    misclass_images.append(i)# image
    misclass_labels.append(k)# truth
    misclass_probas.append(l[0])# predicted probability
    misclass_index.append(count)# save index from database

# Sort by increasing probability (one liner!)
misclass_probas,misclass_labels,misclass_images = map(list, zip(*sorted(zip(misclass_probas,misclass_labels,misclass_images), reverse=True)))
In [ ]:
# Visualize all the misclassified from CNN0:
print(len(misclass_probas))# there are 129 misclassified images
np.random.seed()
plt.figure(1 , figsize = (24 , 24))

for n in range(0, 129):
    plt.subplot(11, 12, n+1)
    index=n# just follow
    # index = int(np.random.randint(0, len(misclass_probas), 1))# any
    # index = int(np.random.randint(0, len(misclass_probas)/4, 1))# first quartile
    # index = int(np.random.randint(3*len(misclass_probas)/4, len(misclass_probas), 1))# last quartile
    plt.imshow(misclass_images[index])
    if misclass_labels[index] == 1:# uninfected
      plt.title(str(misclass_index[index])+' - '+str(round(misclass_probas[index]*100))+'%')
    else:
      plt.title(str(misclass_index[index])+' - '+str(round(misclass_probas[index]*100))+'%',color='r')

    plt.axis('off')

132

Notes on misclassified images:

The above figure shows all 129 misclassified images by CNN0 from the test dataset. The title (in black for uninfected cell, red for parasitized cell) show the image index in the database as well as the predicted probability of being parasitized (in %). The images are ordered by decreasing probability:

  • The misclassified uninfected (with predicted proba around 100%) cells have either disformed shapes, or a very small light center (that might be confused for a malaria parasite)
  • The misclassified parasitized cells (with predicted proba around 0%) may have a very small malaria parasite, or a malaria parasite that is cropped or a the cell edge.
  • The cells with predicted proba around 50% have very disformed shapes that are likely to be outliers in the database.

Notes on CNN1:¶

The model CNN1 is the CNN0 with an additional dense (fully-connected layer) of 512 weights:

  • It doesnt really improve accuracy (95%) or other metrics compared to CNN0.
  • This suggests that the additional dense layer is unecessary (at least at this stage of exploration).

Model CNN2 with Leaky Relu and Batch Normalization¶

Let build a model CNN2 that is CNN0 with BatchNormalization and replacing Relu with LeakyRelu as our activation function (except for the final binary classification which always uses sigmoid).

  • Can the model performance be improved if we change our activation function to LeakyRelu?
  • Can BatchNormalization improve our model? It is usually used to speed up convergence, and also regularizes the model as a side-effect.

Notes:

  • LeakyRelu replaces Relu for all activation function except the final binary classification (that is always sigmoid/softmax)
  • It is advised against using Batch Normalization and Dropout altogether (due to noisy statistics used to normalize), cf Deep Learning 2016 p 425.

Model CNN3 with Data Augmentation¶

Lets build a model CNN3 with Data Augmentation. Can it improve the model performances? References to image data augmentation can be seen below:

  • Image Augmentation for Computer Vision
  • How to Configure Image Data Augmentation in Keras?
In [ ]:

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

# Using ImageDataGenerator to generate images

train_datagen = ImageDataGenerator(horizontal_flip=True, 
                                  zoom_range = 0.5, rotation_range=30)
val_datagen  = ImageDataGenerator()# no transformations on validation dataset

# Flowing training images using train_datagen generator
train_generator = train_datagen.flow(x = X_train, y = y_train, batch_size=64, seed=42, shuffle=True)     

# Flowing validation images using val_datagen generator

Visualizing Augmented images

In [ ]:
#Creating an iterable for images and labels from the training data
images, labels = next(train_generator)

#Plotting 16 images from the training data
fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 4, figsize = (16, 8))
fig.set_size_inches(16, 16)
for (image, label, ax) in zip(images, labels, axes.flatten()):
    ax.imshow(image)
    if label[1] == 1:# Remember we have one-hot-encoded label (to uninfected=[1,0],parasitized=[1,0]) 
        ax.set_title('parasitized',color='r')
    elif label[0] == 1:
        ax.set_title('uninfected')
    else:
        ax.set_title('label error')
    ax.axis('off')

Observations and insights: Data Augmentation has a great potential because there are very natural invariances in the database of red cell images. In fact, each red cell is arbitrarily framed to fit perfectly in a squared surface:

  • Rotations of +90, +180, +270 can naturally occur depending on the random orientation of the red cell during framing.
  • Similarly, a horizontal flip (or redundant vertical flip) can naturally occur if the red cell is flipped within the thin blood smear.
  • However, rotations with arbitrary angles doesnt respect the framing and is likely unecessary.
  • The zoom transformation however seems inadequate here, because it doesnt respect the framing. The resulting images are too different from the ones of the original database. For example, a reduced zoom results in spurious strides.
  • Other transformations may be useful as well such as changing brightness and adding noise.

# Fix the bottom layers of the VGG16 (cant train)
transfer_layer = vgg.get_layer('block5_pool')
vgg.trainable=False

# Setup the top layers of the VGG16
x = Flatten()(transfer_layer.output) #Flatten the output from the 3rd block of the VGG16 model
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.3)(x)
x = Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization()(x)
pred = Dense(2, activation='softmax')(x)# final classification layer

# Combine bottom (fixed) and top layers
model4 = Model(vgg.input, pred)

In [ ]:
# Load model CNN0
from tensorflow.keras.models import load_model
model = load_model('/content/drive/MyDrive/Data/CNN0.h5')

y_pred_proba = model.predict(test_images)# predicted probability (two classes)
y_pred = np.argmax(y_pred_proba,axis = -1)# convert boolean
y_true = np.argmax(test_labels,axis = -1)

# Build database of misclassified images
misclass_images=[]
misclass_labels=[]
misclass_probas=[]# predicted probability 0-1
misclass_index=[]# save index from full database
for count,(i,j,k,l) in enumerate(zip(test_images,y_pred,y_true,y_pred_proba)):
  if j != k:
    misclass_images.append(i)# image
    misclass_labels.append(k)# truth
    misclass_probas.append(l[0])# predicted probability
    misclass_index.append(count)# save index from database

# Sort by increasing probability (one liner!)
misclass_probas,misclass_labels,misclass_images = map(list, zip(*sorted(zip(misclass_probas,misclass_labels,misclass_images), reverse=True)))

Model CNN5 ¶

We build a model CNN5. As compared to CNN0 it uses more convolution layers (increasing progressively in size), and more dense layers (i.e. increase in depth).

In [ ]:
import tensorflow as tf
from keras import layers
from keras.layers import Dropout , Input, Add, Dense, Activation, ZeroPadding2D, BatchNormalization, Flatten, Conv2D, AveragePooling2D, MaxPooling2D, GlobalMaxPooling2D
from keras.models import Model, load_model
from keras.initializers import glorot_uniform

# Model CNN5 buildup
inp = Input(shape = (64 , 64 , 3))
x = Conv2D(filters = 16 , kernel_size = (3,3) , strides = (1,1) , padding = "same" , kernel_initializer=glorot_uniform(seed = 2))(inp)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Conv2D(filters = 32 , kernel_size = (4,4) , strides = (2,2) , padding = "same" , kernel_initializer=glorot_uniform(seed = 2))(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2) , strides = (2,2) , padding = "same")(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Conv2D(filters = 64 , kernel_size = (3,3) , strides = (2,2) , padding = "same" , kernel_initializer = glorot_uniform(seed = 2))(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Conv2D(filters = 128 , kernel_size = (3,3) , strides = (1,1) , padding = "same" , kernel_initializer = glorot_uniform())(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2) , strides = (2,2) , padding = "same")(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Conv2D(filters = 256 , kernel_size = (2,2) , strides = (2,2) , padding = "same" , kernel_initializer = glorot_uniform())(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = AveragePooling2D(pool_size = (3,3) , strides = (1,1) , padding = "same")(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dense(128)(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Dense(64)(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Dense(32)(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = Dense(2)(x)
output = Activation("softmax")(x)
model5  = Model(inputs =inp , outputs = output )
model5.summary()

Notes on CNN5:¶

The CNN5 model uses a simple yet efficient architecture, and reaches around 95% accuracy like the other models.

  • The architecture consists of 5 convolution layers (along with 2 max pool and one average pool layers) and 3 fully-connected layers.
  • This is a very deep CNN, yet it only has ~400 000 trainable parameters, much less than CNN0.
  • The model trains very fast, (2 epochs, around 30 seconds) and for these reasons is a favorite.
